The student knows the role of selling in a private enterprise economy.
The student is expected to: (A) (B) explain how selling contributes to economic activity; describe the process of selecting and merchandising apparel and accessory products; and demonstrate steps in the selling process using fashion products.
(C) (14) The student knows the nature and scope of fashion.
The student is expected to: (A) (B ) explain the importance of fashion; demonstrate knowledge of fashion history and how it relates to today's fashions; distinguish among fashion terms (such as fashion, style, and design); list major environmental influences on fashion demand; research fashion information; and explain legislation that impacts the fashion industry.
(C) (D) (E) (F) (15) The student knows that a career in fashion marketing requires knowledge of textiles and design.
The student is expected to: (A) explain how the development of textiles has influenced the fashion industry; differentiate between natural and synthetic fibers; explain elements and principles of design in fashion apparel; list the steps from apparel design to the finished product; and research the use of technology in fashion design, production, and distribution.
